item.title: Laser engraving and cutting test files
item.description:
Using new materials to cut or engrave with your laser cutter/engraver needs some testing before the actual 'work'.

Several test files are online. A lot of them take many time to get ready, especially when cutting is tested because some materials/thicknesses need multiple passes. So I made a simple set of gcode files to make life easier.

A test needs just 10cm by 10cm

Step 1. Just for positioning. It draws a 10cm by 10cm box with the laser at 1%. This step could be skipped since you probably have a laser which can also draw a frame to do the same.

Step 2: engraving the labels on top and on the side.

Step 3a is for test cutting, 3b is for test engraving.
Engraving will just run once, engraving 25 boxes of 1cm by 1cm in a 5 by 5 grid
Cutting will run up to 10 passes. Before each pass it will put a little I in the box with the word passes on top. Each pass it will add one I. After 4 passes, the line for the fifth pass wil go diagonally through the previous 4 lines. Then it starts with another set blow the first set of lines.
After 1 full pass the laser will return home and pause 10 seconds so you have some time to stop the laser if the desired number of passes has been reached (full cut through the material for instance)

Both cutting and engraving will start bottom left. First engraving/cutting at low power and high speed. Each new box will be first at a lower speed, then higher power. So power will increase while speed decreases. My engraving example (see photo) I should have stopped my laser engraver a little sooner before the last (way to heavy engraved) box was drawn.

Step 4 is cutting the box around the test. Depending on the material you have to run this multiple times.

item.title: Laser Adapter Compact Trifan
item.description:
I was messaged by commputethis, a fellow Thingverse user and contributor, to see if I could fit an existing Laser adapter to the Compact Trifan Extruder housing that was designed to fit the stock metal extruder housing on the Ender3/Ender3Pro. Here is a link to the original design, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4835570.

The original design was made to utilize the magnets on the laser housing to secure the adapter and laser to the stock metal extruder housing. Since the Compact Trifan housing is not metal and has different overall dimensions, a complete remix was required. I printed out the original design in order to get the general dimensions for the laser fitment, and then proceeded to redesign it to fit the standard version of the Compact Trifan housing.

Dave (commputethis) was very helpful in providing feedback, since I did not have a laser device in my possession at the time. After a few iterations and tests, we were able to get everything to fit securely and work properly. I have uploaded two versions of the Laser Adapter. One is for the standard depth housing and the other is for the Noctua depth housing. Dave also provided the photos of the part with laser as well. Thanks for the help Dave.

item.title: myRCar
item.description:
Hi,

I'm creating this post to share with you what I changed on original projects to build my own myRCar... It is running very well and is faster and more reliable than I was expecting, for a car that is all printed in PETG (just few parts in PLA), standard TPU (with 95A shore) and TPE (FilaFlex with 82A shore).

I started to print the cool project "Chasis 1/10 Adaptable by dukedoks" and then I started to add more features and improving some thing that was not woring well for my project.

My first modification or add-on it was to add an differential, I found this cool project "Differential" by SlovakFan83". With this differential I no longer get problems driving the car on straight line and whren changing direction is mutch more resposnsive and precise.
For this differencial I have designed a case that you can print and use it if you want to protect your differential gears from dust.

After I saw also this project "Custom RC Car with 1/10 Adaptable Chassis Remix" by DBIANX" and from this project I selected only the rear struture to add the rear Spoiler and the two shocks (60mm).
Also I printed the body case just to protect eletronics (but I will try to design in futture my own body case to this project).

Finally and because I was getting problems with tires from inicial project (because I was priting them with TPU 95A) and they were to small, I found this project "Lynx - Fully 3D-printable 1/10 4wd buggy by tahustvedt" where I redesign the rear rims to use them with rear differential. In future I will also redesign front rims and add them also here.

Notice that I did a lot of research to try to find the best rubberised material and the best one that I found and it's working very well is the FilaFlex 82A. It's not a cheap filament but if we sum the amount that we will pay for a new set of tires is a really good deal. Because to print these two rear tires Prusa Slicer calcutated the final cost of that print in 4.14€. With this amount I'm not able to by on Amazon a set o tires and at same time I save time because I don't need to wait the shipping time ;) I just print during night and in morning I have a new set of tires ;) ready to burn!

Printed parts:

  • Tiers were printed without infill.
  • All body parts were printed on PETG with 8% infill (Brand Tucab - Is a Portuguese Filament Company)
  • Differential gears were printed in PETG with 100% infill (Brand Tucab)
  • Motor gear were printed in PLA with 100% infill (Brand Tucab)

For the eletronics I have used:

  • brushless motor that is very very :O (DollaTek 3660 with 3300 KV and 60A ESC) (Amazon)
  • GOLDBAT RC Battery 2S 5200 mAh 7,4 V 80C LiPo 2S RC and also OVONIC Battery LiPo RC 2200 mAh 7,4 V 2S 50C (Amazon)
  • AZDelivery MG995 Micro Digital Servo Motor (Amazon)
  • Tongdejing Mini Gyro (https://www.amazon.es/-/pt/dp/B08XVNZ6LL/ref=sr_1_1?crid=1MBRMF3UWWUEO&keywords=tongdejing+mini+modulo+gyro&qid=1643228046&s=toys&sprefix=tongdejing+mini+m%C3%B3dulo+gyro%2Ctoys%2C75&sr=1-1) (Amazon)
  • Radio Control is the Flysky 2.4g 10ch FS-i6S

Also all the creadits are from the inicial designers and there projects. I just did some ajustments.

item.title: Courier Singleship (small freighter spaceship)
item.description:
Here's a model of a spaceship for space-port scenarios in sci-fi skirmish games (or whatever other uses you can think of for it). I tried to make it of a realistic size, so it ends up quite a large model for 28mm - I used the size of modern single-seat military aircraft as a rough guide.

It will also make a decent toy spaceship for kids.

The uncut stl prints whole, positioned on my Ender 3 FDM printer if scaled down to 33% size (but will definitely need supports). The landing struts will be a little fragile if scaled down, so remove supports carefully

I included holes to accommodate bits of 1.7mm plastic filament in the mating faces of the cut up version parts to aid alignment during assembly, which I suggest you do with superglue or epoxy.
